      "message": "Yeah, I knew we\u0027d be using the interpreter, at least initially. When I did the earlier work converting the interpreter unit tests to SkVM, I had a decision about how to handle functions that took multiple/vector parameters:\n\n  void main(inout half4 color) {}\n\nCould be four float args, or one float4 arg. I was tempted to do the latter, because (most) SkSL types bottom out at 1-4 32-bit values. Matrices are an exception, but the one that stopped me was float3 -- I guess I can still use a stride of 24, but there\u0027s no load96, obviously. I guess I\u0027d just use a pair of load64 and load32 for any 3-float component?\n\nEven if I tried to go this route, it wouldn\u0027t reduce the pointer count enough (eg, only unpacking the Particle and Effect structs to their constituent vectors) - I\u0027d have to just group fields into 128-bit chunks (which is totally doable).",
